{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_018wm9uCYHFkoydWCP3x5Y1M","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the key questions framework.\n\n**Behavior 1**: Valid JSON payloads containing markdown-heavy strings parse successfully and proceed through normal hook input handling.\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This tests the parsing of valid JSON with markdown content (code fences, backticks, $vars). This is a single function's logic - does the JSON parser handle these characters correctly? The failure mode is at the parsing level, not at a module boundary.\n- REAL-INFRA: No OS/network/subprocess needed. JSON parsing is in-process.\n- MOCK-HIDE: No real external dependencies to mock.\n\n\n- LLM-DEP: No AI/ML involved.\n- MULTI-STEP: No.\n\nThis is a unit test - testing that a JSON parser correctly handles markdown-heavy strings, with failure manifesting in the parsing logic itself.\n\nEVIDENCE-LEVEL: Unit\nOUTPUT-LEVEL: Unit\n\n**Behavior 2**: Truly malformed JSON payloads produce a `json_parse_failed` trace record with enough context to diagnose the malformed section.\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This involves the parser AND the trace sink - when the parser fails, does it emit a trace record? This crosses module boundaries between parser and trace/telemetry.\n- REAL-INFRA: No OS/network needed.\n\nAn in-process fake trace sink can verify this. Using a real in-process trace sink or test double that records calls lets us confirm the trace record is emitted with the right content, so a stub won't hide the failure.\n\nIntegration - the parser needs to be wired to the trace sink to verify the trace record is produced correctly.\n\nEVIDENCE-LEVEL: Integration\nINTEGRATION-BRAKE: \n(a) Real OS/network? No.\n(b) Real AI/ML? No.\n(c) Multiple agentic steps? No.\nOUTPUT-LEVEL: Integration\n\n**Behavior 3**: The local error-policy path maps parse failure to a handled result (no throw) and marks telemetry intent.\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is testing the error-policy module's behavior when it receives a parse failure. The key question is whether \"marks telemetry intent\" means setting a field on the result object or calling out to a separate telemetry module. If it's just a field, this is Unit - testing the error policy function in isolation. If telemetry is a separate module, it becomes Integration. The behavior itself is straightforward: take an error, return a handled result without throwing, and mark telemetry. If \"telemetry intent\" is just a flag on the result object, this is Unit.\n\nNow looking at the fourth behavior about real process execution with malformed stdin. This explicitly requires spawning an actual subprocess and can't be mocked without hiding the real behavior around exit codes and signal emission. This is a System-level test.\n\nFor the fifth behavior, I'm distinguishing between the subprocess execution (behavior 4) and the end-to-end invocation pipeline (behavior 5). The wording \"invocation path\" and \"trace artifact\" suggests testing the full chain from stdin through parser to trace sink, but it's less clear whether this requires actual subprocess execution or could be tested in-process with the modules wired together. The key difference is that behavior 4 explicitly mentions process exit, while behavior 5 focuses on the artifact output from the pipeline. I'm settling on System for behavior 5 because the \"real hook invocation path\" combined with stdin reading and trace artifact production suggests actual process involvement or concrete filesystem output, even though there's some ambiguity about whether this means subprocess execution or just the in-process wiring with real I/O.\n\nFor behavior 6, I'm looking at how the regression tests distinguish between malformed JSON failures and valid markdown payloads to avoid incorrectly blaming the markdown content itself. The full pipeline test with both valid and malformed inputs could push this to Integration level if it exercises the complete parsing flow, but since the core discrimination happens in the parser logic itself, Unit is the right call. Now I'm mapping out the five behaviors: JSON parsing with markdown is a single-function Unit test, the parser plus trace sink together is Integration, the error-policy function testing its return logic is Unit, explicit subprocess execution is System level, and the real hook invocation path with stdin flowing through the full pipeline is also System.\n\nFor confidence distributions, Behavior 1 leans heavily toward Unit at 0.85, Behavior 2 is solidly Integration at 0.70, Behavior 3 is mostly Unit at 0.70 but has a reasonable Integration possibility at 0.25, and Behavior 4 is clearly System at 0.88.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":10153,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":10153},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"81b30c2a-9968-4b33-a0fe-31caa2660dcb","uuid":"809f2b57-04e0-49f0-860b-97b9fc5fe472"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_018wm9uCYHFkoydWCP3x5Y1M","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_017jpShhS9W3MYyS5QDjjUZy","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Valid JSON payloads containing markdown-heavy strings parse successfully and proceed through normal hook input handling.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is in the parser itself — does the JSON tokenizer mishandle code fences, backticks, or `$vars`? This is a single function's logic boundary, not a module handoff failure. REAL-INFRA: No OS/network/subprocess needed; an in-process call to the parser with a crafted string string reproduces the exact failure. MOCK-HIDE: No dependency to mock. LLM-DEP: None. MULTI-STEP: None. COMMIT-TO-REASONING: Evidence points to Unit (parser correctness on valid but tricky input). REJECTION-GATE: Integration was considered but rejected because the failure manifests entirely within the parsing call — no module boundary is crossed to expose it.","test_description":"Feed the JSON parser a set of valid JSON strings whose values contain markdown constructs (triple backtick code fences, inline backticks, `$VAR` style strings, backslash sequences). Assert the return value equals the expected parsed object and no exception is raised.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.85,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Truly malformed JSON payloads produce a `json_parse_failed` trace record with enough context to diagnose the malformed section.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode spans the boundary between the parser (which signals an error) and the trace/telemetry sink (which must record the structured `json_parse_failed` event with context). A unit test on the parser alone cannot confirm the trace record is produced with the right shape. REAL-INFRA: No OS/network needed — an in-process trace collector stub can intercept the trace emission without real I/O. MOCK-HIDE: A fully mocked trace sink that doesn't validate record fields would hide missing context fields. COMMIT-TO-REASONING: Evidence points to Integration (parser-to-trace-sink handoff). INTEGRATION-BRAKE: (a) No real OS/network. (b) No AI/ML. (c) No agentic chaining. OUTPUT-LEVEL matches EVIDENCE-LEVEL.","test_description":"Wire the parser to a real (or test-double) trace collector. Supply a definitively malformed JSON string (e.g., truncated object, unescaped control character). Assert the collector received exactly one `json_parse_failed` record, that the record includes the malformed input excerpt or byte offset, and that no exception propagates to the caller.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.12,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The local error-policy path maps parse failure to a handled result (no throw) and marks telemetry intent.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The behavior describes a local error-policy function's contract: receive a parse error, return a handled result (no exception), set a telemetry-intent field. 'Marks telemetry intent' reads as setting a field on the result object, not calling a separate telemetry service — the entire logic is within the error-policy module. REAL-INFRA: None needed. MOCK-HIDE: No external dependency to mock. LLM-DEP: None. COMMIT-TO-REASONING: Evidence is Unit. If 'marks telemetry intent' required calling a separate telemetry module that could fail independently, the level would be Integration — but the behavior text says 'local error-policy path', implying self-contained logic. REJECTION-GATE: Integration rejected because no concrete cross-module handoff is named in the behavior description.","test_description":"Call the error-policy handler directly with a synthetic parse-failure error value. Assert: (a) no exception is raised, (b) the returned result object carries a handled/non-fatal status, (c) the result's telemetry-intent flag/field is set to the expected value indicating a parse failure was observed.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.68,"Integration":0.28,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"In real process execution, malformed stdin does not crash the hook process and still emits the expected trace signal before exit.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"MOCK-MISS and REAL-INFRA: The behavior explicitly says 'real process execution' — the failure modes are OS-level: the process crashing (non-zero exit, SIGABRT, unhandled exception killing the process), stdin stream behavior, and signal/trace emission before the OS reclaims the process. These cannot be reproduced by in-process fakes. MOCK-HIDE: An in-process call to the parser with a fake stdin buffer hides real process lifecycle failures (signal handlers not registered, atexit not firing, buffered trace not flushed before exit). COMMIT-TO-REASONING: Evidence clearly points to System. REJECTION-GATE: Integration rejected — the behavior explicitly names 'real process execution' and 'before exit', which are OS-level primitives no in-process fake can replicate.","test_description":"Spawn the hook binary as a subprocess via the test runner. Write malformed JSON bytes to its stdin, then close stdin. Assert: (a) the process exits with a non-crash exit code (not SIGABRT/139), (b) the process's stdout or a named trace file contains the expected trace signal token before the process exits, (c) the exit occurs within a reasonable timeout.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.9,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"A real hook invocation path (stdin -> parser -> trace sink) produces the expected trace artifact when malformed input is supplied.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"MOCK-MISS and REAL-INFRA: 'Real hook invocation path' and 'trace artifact' (a concrete output — file, log entry, named pipe record) imply the full stdin-reading pipeline is exercised as it runs in production. The chain stdin→parser→sink involves real I/O: reading from a stream and writing to a concrete artifact. An in-process fake stdin buffer does not reproduce real stream edge cases (partial reads, buffering, EOF handling). MOCK-HIDE: Stubbing stdin as a bytes object in-process hides buffering and EOF behavior; a fake trace sink hides flush/write failures. COMMIT-TO-REASONING: EVIDENCE-LEVEL = System. The 'real' qualifier combined with 'trace artifact' production tips this above Integration. INTEGRATION-BRAKE: (a) stdin is a real I/O stream → System. REJECTION-GATE: Integration rejected because 'real hook invocation path' with stdin I/O and a concrete trace artifact cannot be faithfully reproduced by in-process module wiring alone.","test_description":"Execute the hook's invocation entry point (or spawn it as a subprocess if stdin reading is process-bound). Pipe malformed JSON bytes through its stdin interface. After execution completes, inspect the output trace artifact (file, stdout, or sink record). Assert it contains a `json_parse_failed` entry with the expected fields and that no crash artifact (core dump, unhandled exception log) is present.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.22,"System":0.72,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Regression tests distinguish malformed-JSON failures from valid-markdown payloads, preventing false attribution to markdown content itself.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is misclassification by the parser — treating valid JSON with markdown-heavy values as malformed. This is a discriminability property of the parsing function itself: given input A (valid JSON, markdown values) it must not emit `json_parse_failed`; given input B (genuinely malformed JSON) it must. Both discriminations are within a single parsing call boundary. REAL-INFRA: No OS/network. MOCK-HIDE: No external dependency. LLM-DEP: None. COMMIT-TO-REASONING: Evidence is Unit — two contrasting input classes exercised against the same parsing function. REJECTION-GATE: Integration rejected because there is no cross-module boundary involved in demonstrating that the parser correctly distinguishes the two input classes.","test_description":"Run two parameterized sub-cases against the parser: (1) valid JSON string whose values contain markdown (code fences, backticks, `$vars`) — assert no `json_parse_failed` trace record is emitted and the result is a successful parse; (2) a truly malformed JSON string (e.g., unmatched brace) — assert `json_parse_failed` IS recorded. The test must fail if either case is mis-classified, directly ruling out markdown as a source of parse failures.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.75,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":10153,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":10153},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"81b30c2a-9968-4b33-a0fe-31caa2660dcb","uuid":"2974d761-4def-4022-b298-273347cb5b82"}
